original_dir = pathlib.Path(r"D:\College Files\AAIML\CSCN8010\CSCN8010\train\train")
new_base_dir = pathlib.Path("D:\College Files\AAIML\CSCN8010\CSCN8010\dogs_vs_cats_small")

def make_subset(subset_name, start_index, end_index):
    for category in ("cat", "dog"):
        dir = new_base_dir / subset_name / category
        os.makedirs(dir)
        fnames = [f"{category}.{i}.jpg" for i in range(start_index, end_index)]
        for fname in fnames:
            shutil.copyfile(src=original_dir / fname,
                            dst=dir / fname)

make_subset("train", start_index=0, end_index=1000)
make_subset("validation", start_index=1000, end_index=1500)
make_subset("test", start_index=1500, end_index=2500)

In this step we're splitting our dataset of images into three subsets (train, validation, and test) for the categories "cat" and "dog". Out of 25k images we're sizing down to 5k images.

Step 2 : EDA: Explore the data with relevant graphs, statistics and insights¶

In [7]:
def display_samples(base_dir, class_name, num_samples=9):
    path = os.path.join(base_dir, class_name)
    images = os.listdir(path)[:num_samples]
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(3, 3, figsize=(10, 10))
    for i, ax in enumerate(axes.flat):
        img_path = os.path.join(path, images[i])
        img = Image.open(img_path)
        ax.imshow(img)
        ax.axis("off")
    plt.suptitle(f"Sample Images - {class_name.capitalize()}", fontsize=16)
    plt.show()

base_dir = r"D:\College Files\AAIML\CSCN8010\CSCN8010\dogs_vs_cats_small\train"
display_samples(base_dir, "cat") # Displaying samples for cats and dogs
display_samples(base_dir, "dog")

Here through these sample images, we are looking for the quality for the images whether they are visually clear or not, any mislabelling of the image.

In [8]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

def plot_pixel_distribution(base_dir, class_name):
    path = os.path.join(base_dir, class_name)
    img = cv2.imread(os.path.join(path, os.listdir(path)[0]), cv2.IMREAD_GRAYSCALE)
    plt.hist(img.ravel(), bins=256, range=(0, 256), color='blue')
    plt.title(f"Pixel Intensity Distribution - {class_name.capitalize()}")
    plt.xlabel('Pixel Intensity')
    plt.ylabel('Frequency')
    plt.show()

base_dir = r"D:\College Files\AAIML\CSCN8010\CSCN8010\dogs_vs_cats_small\train"

plot_pixel_distribution(base_dir, "cat")
plot_pixel_distribution(base_dir, "dog")

The peaks in the higher range (around 200–255) suggest that the image has bright areas, possibly background or highlights on the cat.The scattered distribution in the lower range (0–50) indicates darker regions, likely the fur or shadows.

In [9]:
from tensorflow.keras.preprocessing.image import ImageDataGenerator
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

datagen = ImageDataGenerator(
    rotation_range=40,
    width_shift_range=0.2,
    height_shift_range=0.2,
    shear_range=0.2,
    zoom_range=0.2,
    horizontal_flip=True,
    fill_mode='nearest'
)

img = Image.open(r"D:\College Files\AAIML\CSCN8010\CSCN8010\dogs_vs_cats_small\train\cat\cat.0.jpg")
x = np.array(img).reshape((1,) + img.size + (3,))
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 5, figsize=(15, 5))
for i, ax in enumerate(axes.flat):
    batch = next(datagen.flow(x, batch_size=1))
    ax.imshow(batch[0].astype('uint8'))
    ax.axis("off")
plt.suptitle("Augmented Images")
plt.show()

This augmentation enhances the diversity of the training dataset, which helps the model generalize better and avoid overfitting.Ensure that the augmentations do not distort the features crucial for distinguishing between cats and dogs.

In [ ]:
inputs = keras.Input(shape=(180, 180, 3))
x = layers.Rescaling(1./255)(inputs)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=32, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=64, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=128, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=256, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=256, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.Flatten()(x)
outputs = layers.Dense(1, activation="sigmoid")(x)
model = keras.Model(inputs=inputs, outputs=outputs)

import numpy as np

def get_features_and_labels(dataset):
    all_features = []
    all_labels = []
    for images, labels in dataset:
        preprocessed_images = keras.applications.vgg16.preprocess_input(images)
        features = conv_base.predict(preprocessed_images)
        all_features.append(features)
        all_labels.append(labels)
    return np.concatenate(all_features), np.concatenate(all_labels)

train_features, train_labels =  get_features_and_labels(train_dataset)
val_features, val_labels =  get_features_and_labels(validation_dataset)
test_features, test_labels =  get_features_and_labels(test_dataset)

from sklearn.metrics import classification_report, confusion_matrix

cnn_y_pred = (test_model.predict(test_dataset) > 0.5).astype("int32") # Predictions CNN model 
vgg_y_pred = (test_model_vgg.predict(test_features) > 0.5).astype("int32") # Predictions VGG model 

y_true = np.concatenate([y for x, y in test_dataset], axis=0)

print("CNN Model Evaluation:")
print(classification_report(y_true, cnn_y_pred))
print(confusion_matrix(test_labels, cnn_y_pred))

print("\nVGG Model Evaluation:")
print(classification_report(y_true, vgg_y_pred))
print(confusion_matrix(test_labels, vgg_y_pred))

Accuracy:¶

  • CNN Model: 50%
  • VGG Model: 48%
  • The failure of any of the models to differentiate between the two groups suggests that they are not picking up useful characteristics..

Confusion Matrix:¶

  • CNN Model:
  • Misclassifications are almost equal for both classes.
  • Shows no bias towards one class but lacks predictive power
  • VGG Model:
  • Performs slightly better for Class 0 but misclassifies a significant number in Class 1.
  • Likely due to poor training or insufficient tuning.

Precision, Recall, F1-Score:¶

  • All metrics hover around 0.48-0.50, indicating no significant learning.
In [ ]:
from sklearn.metrics import precision_recall_curve
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# CNN Model
precision_cnn, recall_cnn, thresholds_cnn = precision_recall_curve(test_labels, cnn_y_pred)

# VGG Model
precision_vgg, recall_vgg, thresholds_vgg = precision_recall_curve(test_labels, vgg_y_pred)

plt.plot(recall_cnn, precision_cnn, label='CNN')
plt.plot(recall_vgg, precision_vgg, label='VGG')
plt.xlabel('Recall')
plt.ylabel('Precision')
plt.title('Precision-Recall Curve')
plt.legend()
plt.show()
  • CNN (Blue Curve):
  • The curve shows that precision drops significantly as recall increases.
  • The model struggles to balance precision and recall, leading to poor performance.
  • VGG (Orange Curve):
  • The curve is much better, maintaining high precision and recall until the very end.
  • This indicates that VGG performs better than the CNN in balancing precision and recall.

Conclusion:¶

  • The CNN model struggles to learn meaningful patterns, as indicated by the 50% accuracy and poor Precision-Recall curve. This suggests it is equivalent to random guessing.
  • The VGG model performed slightly better, with a Precision-Recall curve showing higher precision and recall compared to the CNN. However, the accuracy of 48% is still
  • The VGG model is better at balancing precision and recall compared to the CNN.
